	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Sat Mar 16, 2013 6:47 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: virtual console Wii</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />So far, no game company that emulates their old games on newer platforms has given us any reason to believe they can do a better job than the enthusiasts that code emulators. I understand why many would think that the companies that made the consoles know more about it than everyone else, but in reality their emulators are often worse than the best ones made by the community. Most problems are sound related, but video issues are not that rare either.<br /><br />I'm sure Nintendo can't handle the NES palette any better than the emulators we use. A lot of things affect how colors look on the NES, and each TV interprets the signal differently, so there simply isn't a magical set of RGB values that can be considered &quot;correct&quot; representations of the NES' colors.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

