		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So far, no game company that emulates their old games on newer platforms has given us any reason to believe they can do a better job than the enthusiasts that code emulators. I understand why many would think that the companies that made the consoles know more about it than everyone else, but in reality their emulators are often worse than the best ones made by the community. Most problems are sound related, but video issues are not that rare either.</div><br />They have different goals than people here, so it's not surprising that theirs doesn't measure up well. They probably want a clean &quot;RGB&quot; look for example. They also probably know that those interested in accuracy either still play the NES, or play emulators, and that it wouldn't be worth the resources to try to win over a small portion of these people. These emulators are a small part of a much larger picture to them. I think they could make very accurate emulators, but it would be extremely costly.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
